docs.abstract: A court found that au pairs were entitled to rights of domestic workers in Massachusetts. Families said they did not know how they would pay. Some au pairs were elated.
docs.snippet: A court found that au pairs were entitled to rights of domestic workers in Massachusetts. Families said they did not know how they would pay. Some au pairs were elated.
docs.lead_paragraph: CAMBRIDGE, Mass. — When Stephanie Mayberg, a physician assistant, learned that a court ruling meant her child care costs were about to increase by 250 percent, she was stunned. The recent federal court decision, that au pairs were entitled to the rights of domestic workers in Massachusetts, including being paid a minimum wage, left Ms. Mayberg, of Southborough, wondering how she and her husband could afford to keep their au pair from Colombia for a second year.

headline.main: A Court Said Au Pairs Deserve Minimum Wage. Some Families Are Protesting.
headline.print_headline: Families Protest Pay Ruling in Favor of Au Pairs

docs.abstract: Before we met, she was my idol. Once we became close, Lizzie enriched my work and life in new ways.
docs.snippet: Before we met, she was my idol. Once we became close, Lizzie enriched my work and life in new ways.
docs.lead_paragraph: A few weeks ago, cleaning out my closet ahead of the new year, I found a skinny purple mohair scarf hand-knit for me by a friend in New York, the memoirist and essayist Elizabeth Wurtzel, who died on Tuesday. I wrapped the scarf around my pet, Frances, a black cat with green eyes identical to Lizzie’s cat Arabella, took a picture and texted it to her. “Remember this scarf?” I wrote.

headline.main: Elizabeth Wurtzel Was a Great Writer and a Better Friend

docs.lead_paragraph: It was a hot day in June, 30 years ago. As the keening crowd surged dangerously toward the grave site, I was lifted off my feet, lost in a heaving mass of humanity.

docs.abstract: The designer Rodolphe Parente is a master of mixing unexpected textures and eras, as his latest project proves.
docs.snippet: The designer Rodolphe Parente is a master of mixing unexpected textures and eras, as his latest project proves.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Paris-based architect and designer Rodolphe Parente refuses to subscribe to a signature style. “On each project, we create a different story; we try to have the right tone, to develop the right emotion,” the 39-year-old says of his narrative-driven approach, which is based on interpreting a client’s desires instead of imposing his own mark. For one recent apartment redesign in Monte Carlo, the unique Mediterranean light and the Modernist building itself inspired Parente to work with textured materials that would be enhanced by the changing shadows; by contrast, in 2015 he transformed a Parisian apartment built in 1910 into a spare futuristic pod with concrete walls and glossy red floors, channeling the client’s devotion to Buddhism, modern architecture and David Lynch.

headline.main: In Paris, an Apartment Where Picassos Meet 17th-Century Antiques
headline.print_headline: By Design; Every Room Tells a Story
